{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01UXMSSoZevD4iugVUEe7S3k","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All requirements are met:\n\n- **Metrics exposed**: RabbitMQ already had `rabbitmq_prometheus` enabled, serving `/metrics` on port 15692 (verified directly from a pod).\n- **3 targets UP**: Prometheus now scrapes all 3 pods (`10.244.0.237/238/239:15692`), all healthy.\n- **`rabbitmq_up` → 3 samples**: each returning `1`.\n- **RabbitMQ healthy**: all 3 pods `Running` / `1/1`, untouched.\n\n## What was wrong and what I changed\n\nThe Prometheus `prometheus-config` ConfigMap only scraped itself — there was no RabbitMQ scrape job. I edited the ConfigMap (native resource, no CRD/operator) to:\n\n1. **Add a `rabbitmq` scrape job using DNS service discovery** on the existing `rabbitmq-headless` service (`type: A`, `port: 15692`). This auto-discovers all 3 pod IPs and requires no API-server RBAC, so the Prometheus ServiceAccount needs no changes.\n2. **Add a recording rule** (`rules.yml`, referenced via `rule_files`) defining `rabbitmq_up = up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}`, since `rabbitmq_up` is not a native plugin metric — this materializes one sample per target (3 total).\n\nThen restarted the Prometheus deployment to load the new config. The RabbitMQ StatefulSet, services, and its config were left untouched."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":131,"cache_creation_input_tokens":575,"cache_read_input_tokens":35778,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":575},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f77ae090-9b11-44a6-9584-0ac3a1946aa0","uuid":"80ec3bec-ec74-41cc-993f-a6a6fa7ba46c","request_id":"req_011Cc9gSuGE3kis4oWJxKawd"}
